@* @foreach over a REASSIGNED List<T> (decision 140): the List twin of ForeachArray (decision 124).
   A List<T> that is never mutated in place but reassigned wholesale has no version signal to bump --
   the FIELD itself is the signal, exactly as a reassigned T[] is. `items` starts [1,2,3]; #add
   reassigns it to `_pool.Where(x => x != 2).ToList()` = [3,4,1,5] -- key 2 is REMOVED, keys 4 and 5
   are INSERTED, keys 1/3 are MOVED, so one click exercises all three reconcile behaviours and #list
   text goes "123" -> "3415", count 3 -> 4, exactly as Blazor's keyed diff renders it. `_pool` is
   never rendered and never written: a plain constant list, not a signal. *@

<ul id="list">
@foreach (int n in items)
{
    <li @key="n">@n</li>
}
</ul>

<button id="add" @onclick="Add">add</button>

@code {
    private List<int> items = new List<int> { 1, 2, 3 };
    private List<int> _pool = new List<int> { 3, 4, 1, 5, 2 };

    private void Add()
    {
        items = _pool.Where(x => x != 2).ToList();
    }
}
